# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: behavior-trees
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Artificial intelligence (AI) in video games refers to the computational systems that control non-player characters (NPCs), generate dynamic game behavior, or simulate strategic decision-making.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] In practice, the term covers a broad range of techniques drawn from computer science, control theory, and robotics rather than "true" artificial intelligence.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Moreover, academic AI—aimed at developing autonomous reasoning or learning—is distinct from game AI, whose goal is to deliver engaging, believable, and efficient behavior for players.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The term *CPU* in video games refer to the AI that control a NPC that could be a playable character in some other situations.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] In general, game AI does not, as might be thought and sometimes is depicted to be the case, mean a realization of an artificial person corresponding to an NPC in the manner of the Turing test or an artificial general intelligence.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Some commentators in the video game industry have claimed that advances in game AI have transformed how players interact with digital systems more broadly.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Marketing discussions sometimes attribute human-like traits to game AI—such as personality or creative autonomy—but these are often scripted behaviors designed to mimic complexity rather than emergent cognition.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Game playing was an area of research in AI from its inception.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] One of the first examples of AI is the computerized game of Nim made in 1941 and published in 1942.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Despite being advanced technology in the year it was made, 20 years before *Pong*, the game took the form of a relatively small box and was able to regularly win games even against highly skilled players of the game.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] In 1951, using the Ferranti Mark 1 machine of the University of Manchester, Christopher Strachey wrote a checkers program and Dietrich Prinz wrote one for chess.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] These were among the first computer programs ever written.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Arthur Samuel's checkers program, developed in the middle 1950s and early 1960s, eventually achieved sufficient skill to challenge a respectable amateur.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Work on checkers and chess would culminate in the defeat of Garry Kasparov by IBM's Deep Blue computer in 1997.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The first video games developed in the 1960s and early 1970s, like *Spacewar!*, *Pong*, and *Gotcha* (1973), were games implemented on discrete logic and strictly based on the competition of two players, without AI.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Games that featured a single player mode with enemies started appearing in the 1970s.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The first notable ones for the arcade appeared in 1974: the Taito game *Speed Race* (racing video game) and the Atari games *Qwak* (duck hunting light gun shooter) and *Pursuit* (fighter aircraft dogfighting simulator).
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Two text-based computer games, *Star Trek* (1971) and *Hunt the Wumpus* (1973), also had enemies.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Enemy movement was based on stored patterns.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The incorporation of microprocessors would allow more computation and random elements overlaid into movement patterns.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] *Galaxian* (1979) added more complex and varied enemy movements, including maneuvers by individual enemies who break out of formation.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] *Pac-Man* (1980) introduced AI patterns to maze games, with the added quirk of different personalities for each enemy.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] *Karate Champ* (1984) later introduced AI patterns to fighting games.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] *First Queen* (1988) was a tactical action RPG which featured characters that can be controlled by the computer's AI in following the leader.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The role-playing video game *Dragon Quest IV* (1990) introduced a "Tactics" system, where the user can adjust the AI routines of non-player characters during battle, a concept later introduced to the action role-playing game genre by *Secret of Mana* (1993).
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Games like *Madden Football*, *Earl Weaver Baseball* and *Tony La Russa Baseball* all based their AI in an attempt to duplicate on the computer the coaching or managerial style of the selected celebrity.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Madden, Weaver and La Russa all did extensive work with these game development teams to maximize the accuracy of the games.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Later sports titles allowed users to "tune" variables in the AI to produce a player-defined managerial or coaching strategy.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The emergence of new game genres in the 1990s prompted the use of formal AI tools like finite-state machines.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Real-time strategy games taxed the AI with many objects, incomplete information, pathfinding problems, real-time decisions and economic planning, among other things.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The first games of the genre had notorious problems.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] *Herzog Zwei* (1989), for example, had almost broken pathfinding and very basic three-state state machines for unit control, and *Dune II* (1992) attacked the players' base in a beeline and used numerous cheats.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Later games in the genre exhibited more sophisticated AI.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Later games have used bottom-up AI methods, such as the emergent behaviour and evaluation of player actions in games like *Creatures* or *Black & White*.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] *Façade* was released in 2005 and used interactive multiple way dialogs and AI as the main aspect of game.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Games have provided an environment for developing artificial intelligence with potential applications beyond gameplay.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Examples include Watson, a Jeopardy!-playing computer; and the RoboCup tournament, where robots are trained to compete in soccer.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Many experts complain that the "AI" in the term *game AI* overstates its worth, as game AI is not about intelligence, and shares few of the objectives of the academic field of AI.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Whereas "real AI" addresses fields of machine learning, decision making based on arbitrary data input, and even the ultimate goal of strong AI that can reason, "game AI" often consists of a half-dozen rules of thumb, or heuristics, that are just enough to give a good gameplay experience.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Historically, academic game-AI projects have been relatively separate from commercial products because the academic approaches tended to be simple and non-scalable.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Commercial game AI has developed its own set of tools, which have been sufficient to give good performance in many cases.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Game developers' increasing awareness of academic AI and a growing interest in computer games by the academic community is causing the definition of what counts as AI in a game to become less idiosyncratic.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Nevertheless, significant differences between different application domains of AI mean that game AI can still be viewed as a distinct subfield of AI.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] In particular, the ability to legitimately solve some AI problems in games by cheating creates an important distinction.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] For example, inferring the position of an unseen object from past observations can be a difficult problem when AI is applied to robotics, but in a computer game a NPC can simply look up the position in the game's scene graph.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Such cheating can lead to unrealistic behavior and so is not always desirable.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] But its possibility serves to distinguish game AI and leads to new problems to solve, such as when and how to cheat.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The major limitation to strong AI is the inherent depth of thinking and the extreme complexity of the decision-making process.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] This means that although it would be then theoretically possible to make "smart" AI the problem would take considerable processing power.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Game AI/heuristic algorithms are used in a wide variety of quite disparate fields inside a game.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The most obvious is in the control of any NPCs in the game, although "scripting" (decision tree) is currently the most common means of control.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] These handwritten decision trees often result in "artificial stupidity" such as repetitive behavior, loss of immersion, or abnormal behavior in situations the developers did not plan for.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Pathfinding, another common use for AI, is widely seen in real-time strategy games.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Pathfinding is the method for determining how to get a NPC from one point on a map to another, taking into consideration the terrain, obstacles and possibly "fog of war".
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Commercial videogames often use fast and simple "grid-based pathfinding", wherein the terrain is mapped onto a rigid grid of uniform squares and a pathfinding algorithm such as A* or IDA* is applied to the grid.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Instead of just a rigid grid, some games use irregular polygons and assemble a navigation mesh out of the areas of the map that NPCs can walk to.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] As a third method, it is sometimes convenient for developers to manually select "waypoints" that NPCs should use to navigate; the cost is that such waypoints can create unnatural-looking movement.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] In addition, waypoints tend to perform worse than navigation meshes in complex environments.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Beyond static pathfinding, navigation is a sub-field of Game AI focusing on giving NPCs the capability to navigate in a dynamic environment, finding a path to a target while avoiding collisions with other entities (other NPC, players...) or collaborating with them (group navigation).
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Navigation in dynamic strategy games with large numbers of units, such as Age of Empires (1997) or Civilization V (2010), often performs poorly; units often get in the way of other units.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Rather than improve the Game AI to properly solve a difficult problem in the virtual environment, it is often more cost-effective to just modify the scenario to be more tractable.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] If pathfinding gets bogged down over a specific obstacle, a developer may just end up moving or deleting the obstacle.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Many contemporary video games fall under the category of action, first-person shooter, or adventure.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] In most of these types of games, there is some level of combat that takes place.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The AI's ability to be efficient in combat is important in these genres.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] A common goal today is to make the AI more human or at least appear so.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] One of the more positive and efficient features found in modern-day video game AI is the ability to hunt.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] AI originally reacted in a very black and white manner.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] If the player were in a specific area then the AI would react in either a complete offensive manner or be entirely defensive.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] In recent years, the idea of "hunting" has been introduced; in this 'hunting' state the AI will look for realistic markers, such as sounds made by the character or footprints they may have left behind.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] These developments ultimately allow for a more complex form of play.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] With this feature, the player can actually consider how to approach or avoid an enemy.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] This is a feature that is particularly prevalent in the stealth genre.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Another development in recent game AI has been the development of "survival instinct".
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] In-game computers can recognize different objects in an environment and determine whether it is beneficial or detrimental to its survival.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Like a user, the AI can look for cover in a firefight before taking actions that would leave it otherwise vulnerable, such as reloading a weapon or throwing a grenade.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] There can be set markers that tell it when to react in a certain way.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] For example, if the AI is given a command to check its health throughout a game then further commands can be set so that it reacts a specific way at a certain percentage of health.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] If the health is below a certain threshold then the AI can be set to run away from the player and avoid it until another function is triggered.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Another example could be if the AI notices it is out of bullets, it will find a cover object and hide behind it until it has reloaded.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Actions like these make the AI seem more human.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] However, there is still a need for improvement in this area.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Another side-effect of combat AI occurs when two AI-controlled characters encounter each other; first popularized in the id Software game *Doom*, so-called 'monster infighting' can break out in certain situations.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Specifically, AI agents that are programmed to respond to hostile attacks will sometimes attack *each other* if their cohort's attacks land too close to them.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] In the case of *Doom*, published gameplay manuals even suggest taking advantage of monster infighting in order to survive certain levels and difficulty settings.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Procedural content generation (PCG) is an AI technique to autonomously create ingame content through algorithms with minimal input from designers.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] PCG is typically used to dynamically generate game features such as levels, NPC dialogue, and sounds.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Developers input specific parameters to guide the algorithms into making content for them.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] PCG offers numerous advantages from both a developmental and player experience standpoint.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Game studios are able to spend less money on artists and save time on production.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Players are given a fresh, highly replayable experience as the game generates new content each time they play.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] PCG allows game content to adapt in real time to the player's actions.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Generative algorithms (a rudimentary form of AI) have been used for level creation for decades.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The iconic 1980 dungeon crawler computer game *Rogue* is a foundational example.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Players are tasked with descending through the increasingly difficult levels of a dungeon to retrieve the Amulet of Yendor.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The dungeon levels are algorithmically generated at the start of each game.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The save file is deleted every time the player dies.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The algorithmic dungeon generation creates unique gameplay that would not otherwise be there as the goal of retrieving the amulet is the same each time.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The roguelike video game genre, derived from *Rogue*, feature games that use some type of procedural generation to provide near infinite replayability.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Opinions on total level generation as seen in games like *Rogue* can vary.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Some developers can be skeptical of the quality of generated content and desire to create a world with a more "human" feel so they will use PCG more sparingly.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Consequently, they will only use PCG to generate specific components of an otherwise handcrafted level.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] A notable example of this is Ubisoft's 2017 tactical shooter *Tom Clancy's Ghost Recon Wildlands*.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Developers used a pathfinding algorithm trained with a data set of real maps to create road networks that would weave through handcrafted villages within the game world.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] This is an intelligent use of PCG as the AI would have a large amount of real world data to work with and roads are straightforward to create.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] However, the AI would likely miss nuances and subtleties if it was tasked with creating a village where people live.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] As AI has become more advanced, developer goals are shifting to create massive repositories of levels from data sets.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] In 2023, researchers from New York University and the University of the Witwatersrand trained a large language model to generate levels in the style of the 1981 puzzle game *Sokoban*.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] They found that the model excelled at generating levels with specifically requested characteristics such as difficulty level or layout.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] However, current models such as the one used in the study require large datasets of levels to be effective.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] They concluded that, while promising, the high data cost of large language models currently outweighs the benefits for this application.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Continued advancements in the field will likely lead to more mainstream use in the future.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The musical score of a video game is an important expression of the emotional tone of a scene to the player.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Sound effects such as the noise of a weapon hitting an enemy help indicate the effect of the player's actions.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Generating these in real time creates an engaging experience for the player because the game is more responsive to their input.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] An example is the 2013 adventure game *Proteus* where an algorithm dynamically adapts the music based on the angle the player is viewing the ingame landscape from.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Recent breakthroughs in AI have resulted in the creation of advanced tools that are capable of creating music and sound based on evolving factors with minimal developer input.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] One such example is the MetaComposure music generator.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] MetaComposure is an evolutionary algorithm designed to generate original music compositions during real time gameplay to match the current mood of the environment.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The algorithm is able to assess the current mood of the game state through "mood tagging".
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Research indicates that there is a significant positive statistical correlation regarding player rated game engagement and the dynamically generated musical compositions when they accurately match their current emotions.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Generative tools similar to those used in LLMs and diffusion models like Midjourney and DALL-E have been used to generate in-game environments, and companies like Ubisoft have stated that they are experimenting with using AI to generate basic dialogue.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Developers at Roblox are using AI to generate 3D objects for players dubbed Cube 3D, an open-source AI that generates 3D objects based on the methods of LLMs to generate words.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Game AI often amounts to pathfinding and finite-state machines.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Pathfinding gets the AI from point A to point B, usually in the most direct way possible.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] State machines permit transitioning between different behaviors.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The Monte Carlo tree search method provides a more engaging game experience by creating additional obstacles for the player to overcome.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The MCTS consists of a tree diagram in which the AI essentially plays tic-tac-toe.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Depending on the outcome, it selects a pathway yielding the next obstacle for the player.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] In complex video games, these trees may have more branches, provided that the player can come up with several strategies to surpass the obstacle.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Academic AI may play a role within game AI, outside the traditional concern of controlling NPC behavior.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Procedural-content generation: Creating elements of the game environment like environmental conditions, levels, and even music in an automated way.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] AI methods can generate new content or interactive stories.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Data mining on user behavior: This allows game designers to explore how people use the game, what parts they play most, and what causes them to stop playing, allowing developers to tune gameplay or improve monetization.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Alternate approaches to NPCs: These include changing the game set-up to enhance NPC believability and exploring social rather than individual NPC behavior.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Rather than procedural generation, some researchers have used generative adversarial networks (GANs) to create new content.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] In 2018 researchers at Cornwall University trained a GAN on a thousand human-created levels for *Doom*; following training, the neural net prototype was able to design new playable levels on its own.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Similarly, researchers at the University of California prototyped a GAN to generate levels for Super Mario.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] In 2020 Nvidia displayed a GAN-created clone of *Pac-Man*; the GAN learned how to recreate the game by watching 50,000 (mostly bot-generated) playthroughs.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Non-player characters are entities within video games that are not controlled by players, but instead are managed by AI systems.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] NPCs contribute to the immersion, storytelling, and the mechanics of a game.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] They often serve as companions, quest-givers, merchants and much more.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Their realism has advanced significantly in the past few years, thanks to improvements in AI technologies.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] NPCs are essential in both narrative-driven as well as open-world games.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] They help convey the lore and context of the game, making them pivotal to world-building and narrative progression.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] For instance, an NPC can provide critical information, offer quests, or simply populate the world to add a sense of realism to the game.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Additionally, their role as quest-givers or merchants makes them integral to the gameplay loop, giving players access to resources, missions, or services that enable further progression.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Additionally, NPCs can be designed to serve functional roles in games, such as a merchant or to provide a service to the player.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] These characters are central to facilitating game mechanics by acting as intermediaries between the player and in-game systems.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Academics say the interactions between players and NPCs are often designed to be straightforward but contextually relevant, ensuring that the player receives necessary feedback or resources for gameplay continuity.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Recent advancements in artificial intelligence have significantly enhanced the complexity and realism of NPCs.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Before these advancements, AI operated on pre-programmed behaviors, making them predictable and repeatable.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] With AI developing NPCs have become more adaptive and able to dynamically respond to players.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Experts think the integration of deep learning and reinforcement learning techniques has enabled NPCs to adjust their behavior in response to player actions, creating a more interactive and personalized gameplay experience.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] One such development is the use of adaptive behavior models.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] These allow NPCs to analyze and learn from players decisions in real time.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] This behavior allows for a much more engaging experience.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] For example as said by experts in the field, NPCs in modern video games can now react to player actions with increased sophistication, such as adjusting their tactics in combat or changing their dialogue based on past interactions.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] By using deep learning algorithms these systems emulate human-like decisions-making, thus making NPCs feel more like real people rather than static game elements.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Another advancements in NPC AI is the use of natural language processing, which allows NPCs to engage in more realistic conversations with players.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Before this NPC dialogue was limited to a fixed set of responses.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] It is said that NLP has improved the fluidity of NPC conversations, allowing them to respond more contextually to player inputs.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] This development has increased the depth and immersion of player-NPC interactions, as players can now engage in more complex dialogues that affect the storyline and gameplay outcomes.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Additionally, deep learning models have allowed NPCs to become more capable of predicting players behaviors.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Deep learning allows NPCs to process large amounts of data and adapt to player strategies, making interactions with them less predictable and more varied.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] This creates a more immersive experience, as NPCs are now able to "learn" from player behavior, which provides a greater sense of realism within the game.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Recent advancements in AI for video games have led to more complex and adaptive behaviors in non-playable characters (NPCs).
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] For instance, AI systems now utilize sophisticated techniques such as decision trees and state machines to enhance NPC interactions and realism, as discussed in "Artificial Intelligence in Games".
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Recent advancements in AI for video games have also focused on improving dynamic and adaptive behaviors in NPCs.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] For example, recent research has explored the use of complex neural networks to enable NPCs to learn and adapt their behavior based on player actions, enhancing the overall gaming experience.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] This approach is detailed in the IEEE paper on "AI Techniques for Interactive Game Systems".
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Despite all of these advancements in NPC AI, there are still significant challenges that developers face in designing NPCs.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] They need to balance realism, functionally, and players expectations.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The key challenge is to make sure that NPCs enhance the players experience, rather than disturb the gameplay.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Overly realistic NPCs that behave unpredictably can frustrate players by hindering progression or breaking immersion.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Conversely, NPCs that are too predictable or simplistic may fail to engage players, reducing the overall effectiveness of the game's narrative and mechanics.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Another factor that needs to be accounted for is the computation cost of implementing advanced AI for NPCs.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The use of these Advanced AI techniques requires large amount of processing power, which can limit its usage.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Balancing the performance of AI-driven NPCs with the game's overall technical limitations is crucial for ensuring smooth gameplay.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Experts mentioned how developers must allocate resources efficiently to avoid overburdening the game's systems, particularly in large, open-world games where numerous NPCs must interact with the player simultaneously.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Finally, creating NPCs that can respond dynamically to a wide range of player behaviors remains a difficult task.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] NPCs must be able to handle both scripted interactions and unscripted scenarios where players may behave in unexpected ways.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Designing NPCs capable of adapting to such variability requires complex AI models that can account for numerous possible interactions, which can be resource-intensive and time-consuming for developers.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] In the context of artificial intelligence in video games, cheating refers to the programmer giving agents actions and access to information that would be unavailable to the player in the same situation.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Believing that the Atari 8-bit could not compete against a human player, Chris Crawford did not fix a bug in *Eastern Front (1941)* that benefited the computer-controlled Russian side.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] *Computer Gaming World* in 1994 reported that "It is a well-known fact that many AIs 'cheat' (or, at least, 'fudge') in order to be able to keep up with human players".
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] For example, if the agents want to know if the player is nearby they can either be given complex, human-like sensors (seeing, hearing, etc.), or they can cheat by simply asking the game engine for the player's position.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Common variations include giving AIs higher speeds in racing games to catch up to the player or spawning them in advantageous positions in first-person shooters.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The use of cheating in AI shows the limitations of the "intelligence" achievable artificially; generally speaking, in games where strategic creativity is important, humans could easily beat the AI after a minimum of trial and error if it were not for this advantage.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Cheating is often implemented for performance reasons where in many cases it may be considered acceptable as long as the effect is not obvious to the player.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] While cheating refers only to privileges given specifically to the AI—it does not include the inhuman swiftness and precision natural to a computer—a player might call the computer's inherent advantages "cheating" if they result in the agent acting unlike a human player.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Sid Meier stated that he omitted multiplayer alliances in *Civilization* because he found that the computer was almost as good as humans in using them, which caused players to think that the computer was cheating.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Developers say that most game AIs are honest but they dislike players erroneously complaining about "cheating" AI.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] In addition, humans use tactics against computers that they would not against other people.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] In short, cheating AI is when the game seems to break its own rules, producing impossible outcomes.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The opposite is dynamic difficulty, a structured adjustment of AI skill to maintain competition, respecting game mechanics.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Some games may have a blend of both of these systems at once.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] In the 1996 game *Creatures*, the user "hatches" small furry animals and teaches them how to behave.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] These "Norns" can talk, feed themselves, and protect themselves against vicious creatures.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] It was the first popular application of machine learning in an interactive simulation.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Neural networks are used by the creatures to learn what to do.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The game is regarded as a breakthrough in artificial life research, which aims to model the behavior of creatures interacting with their environment.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] In the 2001 first-person shooter *Halo: Combat Evolved* the player assumes the role of the Master Chief, battling various aliens on foot or in vehicles.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Enemies use cover very wisely, and employ suppressing fire and grenades.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The squad situation affects the individuals, so certain enemies flee when their leader dies.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Attention is paid to the little details, with enemies notably throwing back grenades or team-members responding to being bothered.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The underlying "behavior tree" technology has become very popular in the games industry since *Halo 2*.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The 2005 psychological horror first-person shooter *F.E.A.R.* has player characters engage a battalion of cloned super-soldiers, robots and paranormal creatures.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The AI uses a planner to generate context-sensitive behaviors, the first time in a mainstream game.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] This technology is still used as a reference for many studios.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The Replicas are capable of utilizing the game environment to their advantage, such as overturning tables and shelves to create cover, opening doors, crashing through windows, or even noticing (and alerting the rest of their comrades to) the player's flashlight.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] In addition, the AI is also capable of performing flanking maneuvers, using suppressing fire, throwing grenades to flush the player out of cover, and even playing dead.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Most of these actions, in particular the flanking, is the result of emergent behavior.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The survival horror series *S.T.A.L.K.E.R.* (2007–) confronts the player with man-made experiments, military soldiers, and mercenaries known as Stalkers.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The various encountered enemies (if the difficulty level is set to its highest) use combat tactics and behaviors such as healing wounded allies, giving orders, out-flanking the player and using weapons with pinpoint accuracy.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The 2010 real-time strategy game *StarCraft II: Wings of Liberty* gives the player control of one of three factions in a 1v1, 2v2, or 3v3 battle arena.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The player must defeat their opponents by destroying all their units and bases.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] This is accomplished by creating units that are effective at countering opponents' units.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Players can play against multiple different levels of AI difficulty ranging from very easy to Cheater 3 (insane).
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The AI is able to cheat at the difficulty Cheater 1 (vision), where it can see units and bases when a player in the same situation could not.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Cheater 2 gives the AI extra resources, while Cheater 3 gives an extensive advantage over its opponent.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Generative artificial intelligence, AI systems that can respond to prompts and produce text, images, and audio and video clips, arose in 2023 with systems like ChatGPT and Stable Diffusion.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] In video games, these systems could create the potential for game assets to be created indefinitely, bypassing typical limitations on human creations.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] For example, the 2024 browser-based sandbox game *Infinite Craft* uses generative AI software, including LLaMA.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] When two elements are being combined, a new element is generated by the AI.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The 2024 browser-based game *Oasis* uses generative AI to simulate the video game *Minecraft*.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] *Oasis* is trained on millions of hours of footage from *Minecraft*, and predicts how the next frame of gameplay looks using this dataset.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] *Oasis* does not have object permanence because it does not store any data.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The 2025 video game *AI2U: With You 'Til The End*, developed by AlterStaff Inc., used ChatGPT for the non-playable characters dialogue in the game.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Generative artificial intelligence has been included to perform video upscaling of game images.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Both NVidia's Deep Learning Super Sampling (DLSS) and AMD's FidelityFX Super Resolution (FSR) have included AI as part of their engine.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] In March 2026, NVidia announced version 5.0 of DLSS to release later in 2026, which among other improvements, includes an AI engine that "infuses pixels with photoreal lighting and materials" as to make existing game graphics appear more realistic.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] NVidia's Jensen Huang said that developers will far more control over how DLSS 5.0 would interact with their games, allowing the developer to tweak lighting and texture adjustments, and that NVidia was continuing to improve the technology before its release.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] However, there are similar concerns in other fields particularly the potential for loss of jobs normally dedicated to the creation of these assets.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Voice actors were one of the first groups to express concern on generative AI use in video games.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The North American actor's union SAG-AFTRA had finished a strike in 2023 against television and film production companies, with the strike concluded on new contract terms that gave actors strong control over whether their voices could be used to train generative AI engines.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Shortly afterward, the union agreed to a contract with AI company Replica Studios to allow union voices to be used to train AI and used in games, with the contract assuring pay and rights protections.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] While the contract was agreed upon by a SAG-AFTRA committee, many members expressed criticism of the move, having not been told of it until it was completed and that the deal did not do enough to protect the actors.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The strike concluded by July 2025 with the affected publishers agreeing to a contract that gave actors stronger control of whether their voices could be used for AI.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] To assure such content was disclosed by game publishers and avoid potential copyright issues, Valve implemented new requirements for games on Steam that the use of pre-generated AI assets or live generation via generative AI must be disclosed on the storefront page.
[src:behavior-trees/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Sweeney criticized this move, as "it makes it much, much, much harder for a game developer to have a chance of success.
[src:behavior-trees/behavior-tree-artificial-intelligence-robotics-and-control] A **behavior tree** is a mathematical model of plan execution used in computer science, robotics, control systems and video games.
[src:behavior-trees/behavior-tree-artificial-intelligence-robotics-and-control] They describe switchings between a finite set of tasks in a modular fashion.
[src:behavior-trees/behavior-tree-artificial-intelligence-robotics-and-control] Their strength comes from their ability to create very complex tasks composed of simple tasks, without worrying how the simple tasks are implemented.
[src:behavior-trees/behavior-tree-artificial-intelligence-robotics-and-control] Behavior trees present some similarities to hierarchical state machines with the key difference that the main building block of a behavior is a task rather than a state.
[src:behavior-trees/behavior-tree-artificial-intelligence-robotics-and-control] Its ease of human understanding make behavior trees less error prone and very popular in the game developer community.
[src:behavior-trees/behavior-tree-artificial-intelligence-robotics-and-control] Behavior trees have been shown to generalize to several other control architectures.
[src:behavior-trees/behavior-tree-artificial-intelligence-robotics-and-control] A behavior based control structure was initially proposed by Rodney Brooks in his paper entitled 'A robust layered control system for a mobile robot'.
[src:behavior-trees/behavior-tree-artificial-intelligence-robotics-and-control] In the initial proposal, a list of behaviors could work as alternatives to one another.
[src:behavior-trees/behavior-tree-artificial-intelligence-robotics-and-control] Later, the approach was extended and generalized into a tree-like organization of behaviors, with extensive application in the game industry as a powerful tool to model the behavior of non-player characters (NPCs).
[src:behavior-trees/behavior-tree-artificial-intelligence-robotics-and-control] They have been extensively used in high-profile video games such as Halo, Bioshock, and Spore.
[src:behavior-trees/behavior-tree-artificial-intelligence-robotics-and-control] Recent works propose behavior trees as a multi-mission control framework for UAV, complex robots, robotic manipulation, and multi-robot systems.
[src:behavior-trees/behavior-tree-artificial-intelligence-robotics-and-control] Behavior trees have now reached the maturity to be treated in Game AI textbooks, as well as generic game environments such as Unity (game engine) and Unreal Engine (see links below).
[src:behavior-trees/behavior-tree-artificial-intelligence-robotics-and-control] Behavior trees became popular for their development paradigm: being able to create a complex behavior by only programming the NPC's actions and then designing a tree structure (usually through drag and drop) whose leaf nodes are actions and whose inner nodes determine the NPC's decision making.
[src:behavior-trees/behavior-tree-artificial-intelligence-robotics-and-control] Behavior trees are visually intuitive and easy to design, test, and debug, and provide more modularity, scalability, and reusability than other behavior creation methods.
[src:behavior-trees/behavior-tree-artificial-intelligence-robotics-and-control] Over the years, the diverse implementations of behavior trees kept improving both in efficiency and capabilities to satisfy the demands of the industry, until they evolved into **event-driven** behavior trees.
[src:behavior-trees/behavior-tree-artificial-intelligence-robotics-and-control] Event-driven behavior trees solved some scalability issues of classical behavior trees by changing how the tree internally handles its execution, and by introducing a new type of node that can react to events and abort running nodes.
[src:behavior-trees/behavior-tree-artificial-intelligence-robotics-and-control] Nowadays, the concept of event-driven behavior tree is a standard and used in most of the implementations, even though they are still called "behavior trees" for simplicity.
[src:behavior-trees/behavior-tree-artificial-intelligence-robotics-and-control] A behavior tree is graphically represented as a directed tree in which the nodes are classified as root, control flow nodes, or execution nodes (tasks).
[src:behavior-trees/behavior-tree-artificial-intelligence-robotics-and-control] For each pair of connected nodes the outgoing node is called parent and the incoming node is called child.
[src:behavior-trees/behavior-tree-artificial-intelligence-robotics-and-control] The root has no parents and exactly one child, the control flow nodes have one parent and at least one child, and the execution nodes have one parent and no children.
[src:behavior-trees/behavior-tree-artificial-intelligence-robotics-and-control] Graphically, the children of a control flow node are placed below it, ordered from left to right.
[src:behavior-trees/behavior-tree-artificial-intelligence-robotics-and-control] The execution of a behavior tree starts from the root which sends ticks with a certain frequency to its child.
[src:behavior-trees/behavior-tree-artificial-intelligence-robotics-and-control] A tick is an enabling signal that allows the execution of a child.
[src:behavior-trees/behavior-tree-artificial-intelligence-robotics-and-control] When the execution of a node in the behavior tree is allowed, it returns to the parent a status **running** if its execution has not finished yet, **success** if it has achieved its goal, or **failure** otherwise.
[src:behavior-trees/behavior-tree-artificial-intelligence-robotics-and-control] A control flow node is used to control the subtasks of which it is composed.
[src:behavior-trees/behavior-tree-artificial-intelligence-robotics-and-control] A control flow node may be either a selector (fallback) node or a sequence node.
[src:behavior-trees/behavior-tree-artificial-intelligence-robotics-and-control] They run each of their subtasks in turn.
[src:behavior-trees/behavior-tree-artificial-intelligence-robotics-and-control] When a subtask is completed and returns its status (success or failure), the control flow node decides whether to execute the next subtask or not.
[src:behavior-trees/behavior-tree-artificial-intelligence-robotics-and-control] Fallback nodes are used to find and execute the first child that does not fail.
[src:behavior-trees/behavior-tree-artificial-intelligence-robotics-and-control] A fallback node will return with a status code of success or running immediately when one of its children returns success or running (see Figure I and the pseudocode below).
[src:behavior-trees/behavior-tree-artificial-intelligence-robotics-and-control] The children are ticked in order of importance, from left to right.
[src:behavior-trees/behavior-tree-artificial-intelligence-robotics-and-control] Sequence nodes are used to find and execute the first child that has not yet succeeded.
[src:behavior-trees/behavior-tree-artificial-intelligence-robotics-and-control] A sequence node will return with a status code of failure or running immediately when one of its children returns failure or running (see Figure II and the pseudocode below).
[src:behavior-trees/behavior-tree-artificial-intelligence-robotics-and-control] The children are ticked in order, from left to right.
[src:behavior-trees/behavior-tree-artificial-intelligence-robotics-and-control] In order to apply control theory tools to the analysis of behavior trees, they can be defined as three-tuple.
[src:behavior-trees/behavior-tree-artificial-intelligence-robotics-and-control] where $k\in \mathbb {N}$ represent the discrete time, and $x\in \mathbb {R} ^{n}$ is the state space of the system modelled by the behavior tree.
[src:behavior-trees/behavior-tree-artificial-intelligence-robotics-and-control] Two behavior trees $T_{i}$ and $T_{j}$ can be composed into a more complex behavior tree $T_{0}$ using a Sequence operator.
[src:behavior-trees/behavior-tree] A **behavior tree** is a structured visual modeling technique used in systems engineering and software engineering to represent system behavior.
[src:behavior-trees/behavior-tree] It utilizes a hierarchical tree diagram composed of nodes and connectors to illustrate control flow and system actions.
[src:behavior-trees/behavior-tree] By replacing ambiguous natural language descriptions with standardized visual elements—such as boxes, arrows, and standard symbols—behavior trees improve clarity, reduce misinterpretation, and enhance understanding of complex systems.
[src:behavior-trees/behavior-tree] The extensive amount of detail involved in describing the numerous requirements of a large-scale system using natural language can lead to short-term memory overload, hindering a comprehensive understanding of the system's needs.
[src:behavior-trees/behavior-tree] Natural language often introduces ambiguities, aliases, inconsistencies, redundancies, and incomplete information to concepts.
[src:behavior-trees/behavior-tree] This creates uncertainty and over-complicates systems.
[src:behavior-trees/behavior-tree] The behavior tree representation attempts to eliminate uncertainty by limiting vocabulary to the original requirements.
[src:behavior-trees/behavior-tree] Large requirement sets may require the help of a composition tree representation that resolves aliases and other vocabulary problems in a prior step.
[src:behavior-trees/behavior-tree] The aim is to produce a deep, accurate, and holistic representation of system needs that can be understood by all readers (often stakeholders).
[src:behavior-trees/behavior-tree] Since the behavior tree notation uses formal semantics, it can serve as input for further processing, such as making an executable for a given set of requirements.
[src:behavior-trees/behavior-tree] Both single and integrated (composite) behavior tree forms are important in applying behavior trees in systems and software engineering.
[src:behavior-trees/behavior-tree] Having all the requirements converted to behavior trees (RBT) is similar to having all the pieces for a jigsaw puzzle randomly spread out on a table – until all the pieces are connected, the emergent picture remains unclear, and it is uncertain whether any pieces are missing or don’t fit.
[src:behavior-trees/behavior-tree] Constructing an integrated behavior tree (IBT) reveals emergent behavior and missing pieces.
[src:behavior-trees/behavior-tree] Critical aspects of behavior engineering representation and process are listed below.
[src:behavior-trees/behavior-tree] Behavior trees and the concepts for their application in systems and software engineering were originally developed by Geoff Dromey.
[src:behavior-trees/behavior-tree] The first publication of some of the key ideas were in 2001.
[src:behavior-trees/behavior-tree] Early publications on this work used the terms "genetic software engineering" and "genetic design" to describe the application of behavior trees.
[src:behavior-trees/behavior-tree] These genetic parallels, in another context, were originally spelled out by Adrian Woolfson.
[src:behavior-trees/behavior-tree] Despite these legitimate genetic parallels, it was felt that this emphasis led to confusion with the concept of genetic algorithms.
[src:behavior-trees/behavior-tree] As a result, the term behavior engineering was introduced to describe the processes that exploit behavior trees to construct systems.
[src:behavior-trees/behavior-tree] Probabilistic timed behavior trees have been developed by researchers such as Rob Colvin, Lars Grunske, and Kirsten Winter of the DCCS, so that reliability, performance, and other dependability properties could be expressed.
[src:behavior-trees/behavior-tree] A behavior tree is used to formally represent the *fragment of behavior* in each requirement.
[src:behavior-trees/behavior-tree] In general, behavior for a large-scale system, where concurrency is admitted, appears abstractly as a set of communicating sequential processes.
[src:behavior-trees/behavior-tree] The behavior tree notation captures these composed component-states and represents them as a tree-like form.
[src:behavior-trees/behavior-tree] Traceability tags (see Section 1.2 of behavior tree notation) in behavior tree nodes link the formal representation to the corresponding natural language requirement.
[src:behavior-trees/behavior-tree] A behavior tree with leaf nodes may revert (symbolized by adding the caret operator "^") to an ancestor node to repeat behavior or start a new thread (symbolized by two carets "^^").
[src:behavior-trees/behavior-tree] For a complete reference to behavior tree notation, see *Behavior Tree Notation v1.0* (2007).
[src:behavior-trees/behavior-tree] The formal semantics of behavior trees is given via a process algebra and its operational semantics.
[src:behavior-trees/behavior-tree] The semantics have been used as the basis for developing simulation, model checking, and failure modes and effects analysis.
[src:behavior-trees/behavior-tree] Once an integrated behavior tree has been composed, there are a number of important operations that can be performed upon it.
[src:behavior-trees/behavior-tree] In general, many defects become much more visible when there is an integrated view of the requirements and each requirement has been placed in the behavior context where it needs to execute.
[src:behavior-trees/behavior-tree] For example, it is much easier to tell whether a set of conditions or events emanating from a node is complete and consistent.
[src:behavior-trees/behavior-tree] The traceability tags also make it easy to refer back to the original natural-language requirements.
[src:behavior-trees/behavior-tree] There is also the potential to automate a number of defect and consistency checks on an integrated behavior tree.
[src:behavior-trees/behavior-tree] When all defects have been corrected and the IBT is logically consistent and complete, it becomes a model behavior tree (MBT), which serves as a formal specification for the system's behavior that has been constructed out of the original requirements.
[src:behavior-trees/behavior-tree] This is the clearly defined stopping point for the analysis phase.
[src:behavior-trees/behavior-tree] With other modeling notations and methods (i.e.
[src:behavior-trees/behavior-tree] UML), it is less clear-cut when modelling can stop.
[src:behavior-trees/behavior-tree] In some cases, parts of a model behavior tree may need to be transformed to make the specification executable.
[src:behavior-trees/behavior-tree] Once an MBT has been made executable, it is possible to carry out a number of other dependability checks.
[src:behavior-trees/behavior-tree] A model behavior tree can be readily simulated to explore the dynamic properties of the system.
[src:behavior-trees/behavior-tree] Both a symbolic tool and a graphics tool have been constructed to support these activities.
[src:behavior-trees/behavior-tree] A translator has been written to convert a model behavior tree into the "actions systems" language.
[src:behavior-trees/behavior-tree] This input can then be fed into the SAL Model checker to allow checks to be made as to whether certain safety and security properties are satisfied.
[src:behavior-trees/behavior-tree] Model checking has often been applied to system models to check that hazardous states can’t be reached during normal operation of the system.
[src:behavior-trees/behavior-tree] It is possible to combine model-checking with behavior trees to provide automated support for failure mode and effects analysis (FMEA).
[src:behavior-trees/behavior-tree] The advantage of using behavior trees for this purpose is that they allow the formal method aspects of the approach to be hidden from non-expert users.
[src:behavior-trees/behavior-tree] Because a system is likely to undergo many changes over its service life, it is necessary to record, manage, and optimize its evolution driven by these changes.
[src:behavior-trees/behavior-tree] A traceability model, which uses behavior trees as a formal notation to represent functional requirements, reveals change impacts on different types of design constructs (documents) caused by the changes of the requirements.
[src:behavior-trees/behavior-tree] The model introduces the concept of evolutionary design documents that record the change history of the designs.
[src:behavior-trees/behavior-tree] From these documents, any version of a design document, as well as the difference between any two versions, can be retrieved.
[src:behavior-trees/behavior-tree] An important advantage of this model is that automated tools can support a major part of the procedure to generate these evolutionary design documents.
[src:behavior-trees/behavior-tree] The behavior tree representation of the integrated behavior of the system offers several important advantages as an executable model.
[src:behavior-trees/behavior-tree] It clearly separates the tasks of *component integration* from the task of individual *component implementation*.
[src:behavior-trees/behavior-tree] The integrated system behavior resulting from requirement integration can serve as a foundation for design decisions.
[src:behavior-trees/behavior-tree] The result is a design behavior tree (DBT): an executable multi-thread component integration specification that has been built out of the original requirements.
[src:behavior-trees/behavior-tree] Behavior tree models are executed in a virtual machine called the behavior run-time environment (BRE).
[src:behavior-trees/behavior-tree] The BRE links together components using middleware, allowing components to be independent programs written in one of several languages that can be executed in a distributed environment.
[src:behavior-trees/behavior-tree] The BRE also contains an expression parser that automatically performs simple operations to minimize the amount of code required to be manually implemented in the component.
[src:behavior-trees/behavior-tree] Executable behavior trees have been developed for case studies including automated train protection, mobile robots with a dynamic object following, an ambulatory infusion pump, and traffic light management systems.
[src:behavior-trees/behavior-tree] A version of the BRE suited for embedded systems (eBRE) is also available, with reduced functionality tailored for small-footprint microcontrollers.
[src:behavior-trees/behavior-tree] Behavior tree modeling can and has been applied to a diverse range of applications over a number of years.
[src:behavior-trees/behavior-tree] Some of the main application areas are described below.
[src:behavior-trees/behavior-tree] Modeling large-scale systems with extensive sets of natural-language requirements has always been a major focus for testing behavior trees and the overall behavior engineering process.
[src:behavior-trees/behavior-tree] Conducting these evaluations and trials of the method has involved work with a number of industry partners and government departments in Australia.
[src:behavior-trees/behavior-tree] The systems studied have included a significant number of defense systems, enterprise systems, transportation systems, information systems, health systems, and sophisticated control systems with stringent safety requirements.
[src:behavior-trees/behavior-tree] The results of these studies have all been classified as commercial-in-confidence.
[src:behavior-trees/behavior-tree] However, the results of the extensive industry trials with Raytheon Australia are presented below in the Industry Section.
[src:behavior-trees/behavior-tree] This work has shown that translating requirements into integrated static and dynamic behavior-tree views revealed substantially more major defects than the company’s standard review processes detected.
[src:behavior-trees/behavior-tree] Failure of a design to meet a system's requirements can result in schedule and cost overruns.
[src:behavior-trees/behavior-tree] If there are also critical dependability issues, not satisfying system requirements can have life-threatening consequences.
[src:behavior-trees/behavior-tree] However, in current approaches, ensuring that requirements are met is often delayed until late in the development process, during a cycle of testing and debugging..
[src:behavior-trees/behavior-tree] This work describes how the system development approach, behavior engineering, can be used to develop software for embedded systems.
[src:behavior-trees/behavior-tree] Many large-scale systems consist of a mixture of co-dependent software and hardware.
[src:behavior-trees/behavior-tree] The different nature of software and hardware means they’re often modeled separately using different approaches.
[src:behavior-trees/behavior-tree] This can subsequently lead to integration problems due to incompatible assumptions about hardware/software interactions.
[src:behavior-trees/behavior-tree] These problems can be overcome by integrating behavior trees with the Modelica mathematical modeling approach.
[src:behavior-trees/behavior-tree] The environment and hardware components are modeled using Modelica and integrated with an executable software model that uses behavior trees.
[src:behavior-trees/behavior-tree] To ensure correct implementation of complex access control requirements, it is important that the validated and verified requirements are effectively integrated with the rest of the system.
[src:behavior-trees/behavior-tree] It is also important that the system can be validated and verified early in the development process.
[src:behavior-trees/behavior-tree] An integrated, role-based access control model has been developed.
[src:behavior-trees/behavior-tree] The model is based on the graphical behavior tree notation and can be validated by simulation, as well as verified using a model checker.
[src:behavior-trees/behavior-tree] The effectiveness of the model has been evaluated using a case study with distributed access control requirements.
[src:behavior-trees/behavior-tree] Because behavior trees describe complex behavior, they can be used for describing a range of systems not limited to those that are computer-based.
[src:behavior-trees/behavior-tree] While behavior trees have become popular for modeling the artificial intelligence in computer games such as Halo and Spore, these types of trees are very different from the ones described on this page and are closer to a combination of hierarchical finite-state machines or decision trees.
[src:behavior-trees/behavior-tree] Soccer-player modeling has also been a successful application of behavior trees.
[src:behavior-trees/behavior-tree] Model-based testing is an approach to software testing that requires testers to create test models from requirements of Software Under Test (SUT).
[src:behavior-trees/behavior-tree] Traditionally, modeling languages such as UML statecharts, finite-state machines (FSMs), extended finite-state machines (EFSMs), and flowcharts have been used.
[src:behavior-trees/behavior-tree] Recently, an interesting approach in which Event-Driven Swim Lane Petri Net (EDSLPN) is used as the modeling language also appeared.
[src:behavior-trees/behavior-tree] It is intuitive to use as a modeling notation due to its graphical nature.
[src:behavior-trees/behavior-tree] Each behavior tree node has a requirement tag; these greatly facilitate the creation of a traceability matrix from requirement to test artifact.
[src:behavior-trees/behavior-tree] The first industry trials to test the feasibility of the method and refine its capability were conducted in 2002.
[src:behavior-trees/behavior-tree] Over the last three years, a number of systematic industry trials on large-scale defense, transportation, and enterprise systems have been conducted.
[src:behavior-trees/behavior-tree] This work has established that the method scales to systems with large numbers of requirements but also that it is important to use tool support in order to efficiently navigate and edit the resultant large integrated views of graphical data.
[src:behavior-trees/behavior-tree] On average, over a number of projects, 130 confirmed major defects per 1000 requirements have consistently been found after normal reviews and corrections have been made.
[src:behavior-trees/behavior-tree] With less mature requirements sets, much higher defect rates have been observed.
[src:behavior-trees/blackboard-system] A **blackboard system** is an artificial intelligence approach based on the blackboard architectural model, where a common knowledge base, the "blackboard", is iteratively updated by a diverse group of specialist knowledge sources, starting with a problem specification and ending with a solution.
[src:behavior-trees/blackboard-system] Each knowledge source updates the blackboard with a partial solution when its internal constraints match the blackboard state.
[src:behavior-trees/blackboard-system] In this way, the specialists work together to solve the problem.
[src:behavior-trees/blackboard-system] The blackboard model was originally designed as a way to handle complex, ill-defined problems, where the solution is the sum of its parts.
[src:behavior-trees/blackboard-system] The **blackboard**, a shared repository of problems, partial solutions, suggestions, and contributed information.
[src:behavior-trees/blackboard-system] The blackboard can be thought of as a dynamic "library" of contributions to the current problem that have been recently "published" by other knowledge sources.
[src:behavior-trees/blackboard-system] The **control shell**, which controls the flow of problem-solving activity in the system.
[src:behavior-trees/blackboard-system] Just as the eager human specialists need a moderator to prevent them from trampling each other in a mad dash to grab the chalk, KSs need a mechanism to organize their use in the most effective and coherent fashion.
[src:behavior-trees/blackboard-system] In a blackboard system, this is provided by the control shell.
[src:behavior-trees/blackboard-system] A blackboard system is the central space in a multi-agent system.
[src:behavior-trees/blackboard-system] It's used for describing the world as a communication platform for agents.
[src:behavior-trees/blackboard-system] To realize a blackboard in a computer program, a machine readable notation is needed in which facts can be stored.
[src:behavior-trees/blackboard-system] One attempt in doing so is a SQL database, another option is the **Learnable Task Modeling Language (LTML)**.
[src:behavior-trees/blackboard-system] The syntax of the LTML planning language is similar to PDDL, but adds extra features like control structures and OWL-S models.
[src:behavior-trees/blackboard-system] LTML was developed in 2007 as part of a much larger project called POIROT (Plan Order Induction by Reasoning from One Trial), which is a Learning from demonstrations framework for process mining.
[src:behavior-trees/blackboard-system] In POIROT, Plan traces and hypotheses are stored in the LTML syntax for creating semantic web services.
[src:behavior-trees/blackboard-system] Here is a small example: A human user is executing a workflow in a computer game.
[src:behavior-trees/blackboard-system] The user presses some buttons and interacts with the game engine.
[src:behavior-trees/blackboard-system] While the user interacts with the game, a plan trace is created.
[src:behavior-trees/blackboard-system] That means the user's actions are stored in a logfile.
[src:behavior-trees/blackboard-system] The logfile gets transformed into a machine readable notation which is enriched by semantic attributes.
[src:behavior-trees/blackboard-system] The result is a textfile in the LTML syntax which is put on the blackboard.
[src:behavior-trees/blackboard-system] Agents (software programs in the blackboard system) are able to parse the LTML syntax.
[src:behavior-trees/blackboard-system] We start by discussing two well known early blackboard systems, BB1 and GBB, below and then discuss more recent implementations and applications.
[src:behavior-trees/blackboard-system] The BB1 blackboard architecture was originally inspired by studies of how humans plan to perform multiple tasks in a trip, used task-planning as a simplified example of tactical planning for the Office of Naval Research.
[src:behavior-trees/blackboard-system] A key innovation of BB1 was that it applied this opportunistic planning model to its own control, using the same blackboard model of incremental, opportunistic, problem-solving that was applied to solve domain problems.
[src:behavior-trees/blackboard-system] Meta-level reasoning with control knowledge sources could then monitor whether planning and problem-solving were proceeding as expected or stalled.
[src:behavior-trees/blackboard-system] If stalled, BB1 could switch from one strategy to another as conditions – such as the goals being considered or the time remaining – changed.
[src:behavior-trees/blackboard-system] BB1 was applied in multiple domains: construction site planning, inferring 3-D protein structures from X-ray crystallography, intelligent tutoring systems, and real-time patient monitoring.
[src:behavior-trees/blackboard-system] BB1 also allowed domain-general language frameworks to be designed for wide classes of problems.
[src:behavior-trees/blackboard-system] For example, the ACCORD language framework defined a particular approach to solving configuration problems.
[src:behavior-trees/blackboard-system] The problem-solving approach was to incrementally assemble a solution by adding objects and constraints, one at a time.
[src:behavior-trees/blackboard-system] Actions in the ACCORD language framework appear as short English-like commands or sentences for specifying preferred actions, events to trigger KSes, preconditions to run a KS action, and obviation conditions to discard a KS action that is no longer relevant.
[src:behavior-trees/blackboard-system] GBB focused on efficiency, in contrast to BB1, which focused more on sophisticated reasoning and opportunistic planning.
[src:behavior-trees/blackboard-system] GBB improves efficiency by allowing blackboards to be multi-dimensional, where dimensions can be either ordered or not, and then by increasing the efficiency of pattern matching.
[src:behavior-trees/blackboard-system] GBB1, one of GBB's control shells implements BB1's style of control while adding efficiency improvements.
[src:behavior-trees/blackboard-system] Other well-known of early academic blackboard systems are the Hearsay II speech recognition system and Douglas Hofstadter's Copycat and Numbo projects.
[src:behavior-trees/blackboard-system] Blackboard systems are used routinely in many military C4ISTAR systems for detecting and tracking objects.
[src:behavior-trees/blackboard-system] Another example of current use is in Game AI, where they are considered a standard AI tool to help with adding AI to video games.
[src:behavior-trees/blackboard-system] Blackboard-like systems have been constructed within modern Bayesian machine learning settings, using agents to add and remove Bayesian network nodes.
[src:behavior-trees/blackboard-system] In these 'Bayesian Blackboard' systems, the heuristics can acquire more rigorous probabilistic meanings as proposal and acceptances in Metropolis Hastings sampling though the space of possible structures.
[src:behavior-trees/blackboard-system] Conversely, using these mappings, existing Metropolis-Hastings samplers over structural spaces may now thus be viewed as forms of blackboard systems even when not named as such by the authors.
[src:behavior-trees/blackboard-system] Such samplers are commonly found in musical transcription algorithms for example.
[src:behavior-trees/blackboard-system] Blackboard systems have also been used to build large-scale intelligent systems for the annotation of media content, automating parts of traditional social science research.
[src:behavior-trees/decision-tree] A **decision tree** is a decision support recursive partitioning structure that uses a tree-like model of decisions and their possible consequences, including chance event outcomes, resource costs, and utility.
[src:behavior-trees/decision-tree] It is one way to display an algorithm that only contains conditional control statements.
[src:behavior-trees/decision-tree] Decision trees are commonly used in operations research, specifically in decision analysis, to help identify a strategy most likely to reach a goal, but are also a popular tool in machine learning.
[src:behavior-trees/decision-tree] A decision tree is a flowchart-like structure in which each internal node represents a test on an attribute (e.g. whether a coin flip comes up heads or tails), each branch represents the outcome of the test, and each leaf node represents a class label (decision taken after computing all attributes).
[src:behavior-trees/decision-tree] The paths from root to leaf represent classification rules.
[src:behavior-trees/decision-tree] In decision analysis, a decision tree and the closely related influence diagram are used as a visual and analytical decision support tool, where the expected values (or expected utility) of competing alternatives are calculated.
[src:behavior-trees/decision-tree] Decision trees are commonly used in operations research and operations management.
[src:behavior-trees/decision-tree] If, in practice, decisions have to be taken online with no recall under incomplete knowledge, a decision tree should be paralleled by a probability model as a best choice model or online selection model algorithm.
[src:behavior-trees/decision-tree] Another use of decision trees is as a descriptive means for calculating conditional probabilities.
[src:behavior-trees/decision-tree] Decision trees, influence diagrams, utility functions, and other decision analysis tools and methods are taught to undergraduate students in schools of business, health economics, and public health, and are examples of operations research or management science methods.
[src:behavior-trees/decision-tree] These tools are also used to predict decisions of householders in normal and emergency scenarios.
[src:behavior-trees/decision-tree] Drawn from left to right, a decision tree has only burst nodes (splitting paths) but no sink nodes (converging paths).
[src:behavior-trees/decision-tree] So used manually they can grow very big and are then often hard to draw fully by hand.
[src:behavior-trees/decision-tree] Traditionally, decision trees have been created manually – as the aside example shows – although increasingly, specialized software is employed.
[src:behavior-trees/decision-tree] The decision tree can be linearized into **decision rules**, where the outcome is the contents of the leaf node, and the conditions along the path form a conjunction in the if clause.
[src:behavior-trees/decision-tree] Decision rules can be generated by constructing association rules with the target variable on the right.
[src:behavior-trees/decision-tree] They can also denote temporal or causal relations.
[src:behavior-trees/decision-tree] Commonly a decision tree is drawn using flowchart symbols as it is easier for many to read and understand.
[src:behavior-trees/decision-tree] Note there is a conceptual error in the "Proceed" calculation of the tree shown below; the error relates to the calculation of "costs" awarded in a legal action.
[src:behavior-trees/decision-tree] The basic interpretation in this situation is that the company prefers B's risk and payoffs under realistic risk preference coefficients (greater than $400K—in that range of risk aversion, the company would need to model a third strategy, "Neither A nor B").
[src:behavior-trees/decision-tree] Another example, commonly used in operations research courses, is the distribution of lifeguards on beaches (a.k.a. the "Life's a Beach" example).
[src:behavior-trees/decision-tree] The example describes two beaches with lifeguards to be distributed on each beach.
[src:behavior-trees/decision-tree] There is maximum budget *B* that can be distributed among the two beaches (in total), and using a marginal returns table, analysts can decide how many lifeguards to allocate to each beach.
[src:behavior-trees/decision-tree] In this example, a decision tree can be drawn to illustrate the principles of diminishing returns on beach #1.
[src:behavior-trees/decision-tree] The decision tree illustrates that when sequentially distributing lifeguards, placing a first lifeguard on beach #1 would be optimal if there is only the budget for 1 lifeguard.
[src:behavior-trees/decision-tree] But if there is a budget for two guards, then placing both on beach #2 would prevent more overall drownings.
[src:behavior-trees/decision-tree] Much of the information in a decision tree can be represented more compactly as an influence diagram, focusing attention on the issues and relationships between events.
[src:behavior-trees/decision-tree] Decision trees can also be seen as generative models of induction rules from empirical data.
[src:behavior-trees/decision-tree] An optimal decision tree is then defined as a tree that accounts for most of the data, while minimizing the number of levels (or "questions").
[src:behavior-trees/decision-tree] Several algorithms to generate such optimal trees have been devised, such as ID3/4/5, CLS, ASSISTANT, and CART.
[src:behavior-trees/decision-tree] Among decision support tools, decision trees (and influence diagrams) have several advantages.
[src:behavior-trees/decision-tree] A few things should be considered when improving the accuracy of the decision tree classifier.
[src:behavior-trees/decision-tree] The following are some possible optimizations to consider when looking to make sure the decision tree model produced makes the correct decision or classification.
[src:behavior-trees/decision-tree] Note that these things are not the only things to consider but only some.
[src:behavior-trees/decision-tree] The accuracy of the decision tree can change based on the depth of the decision tree.
[src:behavior-trees/decision-tree] In many cases, the tree's leaves are pure nodes.
[src:behavior-trees/decision-tree] When a node is pure, it means that all the data in that node belongs to a single class.
[src:behavior-trees/decision-tree] For example, if the classes in the data set are Cancer and Non-Cancer a leaf node would be considered pure when all the sample data in a leaf node is part of only one class, either cancer or non-cancer.
[src:behavior-trees/decision-tree] A deeper tree is not always better when optimizing the decision tree.
[src:behavior-trees/decision-tree] A deeper tree can influence the runtime in a negative way.
[src:behavior-trees/decision-tree] If a certain classification algorithm is being used, then a deeper tree could mean the runtime of this classification algorithm is significantly slower.
[src:behavior-trees/decision-tree] There is also the possibility that the actual algorithm building the decision tree will get significantly slower as the tree gets deeper.
[src:behavior-trees/decision-tree] If the tree-building algorithm being used splits pure nodes, then a decrease in the overall accuracy of the tree classifier could be experienced.
[src:behavior-trees/decision-tree] Occasionally, going deeper in the tree can cause an accuracy decrease in general, so it is very important to test modifying the depth of the decision tree and selecting the depth that produces the best results.
[src:behavior-trees/decision-tree] To summarize, observe the points below, we will define the number D as the depth of the tree.
[src:behavior-trees/decision-tree] The ability to test the differences in classification results when changing D is imperative.
[src:behavior-trees/decision-tree] We must be able to easily change and test the variables that could affect the accuracy and reliability of the decision tree-model.
[src:behavior-trees/decision-tree] The node splitting function used can have an impact on improving the accuracy of the decision tree.
[src:behavior-trees/decision-tree] For example, using the information-gain function may yield better results than using the phi function.
[src:behavior-trees/decision-tree] The phi function is known as a measure of "goodness" of a candidate split at a node in the decision tree.
[src:behavior-trees/decision-tree] The information gain function is known as a measure of the "reduction in entropy".
[src:behavior-trees/decision-tree] In the following, we will build two decision trees.
[src:behavior-trees/decision-tree] One decision tree will be built using the phi function to split the nodes and one decision tree will be built using the information gain function to split the nodes.
[src:behavior-trees/decision-tree] This is the information gain function formula.
[src:behavior-trees/decision-tree] The formula states the information gain is a function of the entropy of a node of the decision tree minus the entropy of a candidate split at node t of a decision tree.
[src:behavior-trees/decision-tree] The phi function is maximized when the chosen feature splits the samples in a way that produces homogenous splits and have around the same number of samples in each split.
[src:behavior-trees/decision-tree] We will set D, which is the depth of the decision tree we are building, to three (D = 3).
[src:behavior-trees/decision-tree] We also have the following data set of cancer and non-cancer samples and the mutation features that the samples either have or do not have.
[src:behavior-trees/decision-tree] If a sample has a feature mutation then the sample is positive for that mutation, and it will be represented by one.
[src:behavior-trees/decision-tree] If a sample does not have a feature mutation then the sample is negative for that mutation, and it will be represented by zero.
[src:behavior-trees/decision-tree] To summarize, C stands for cancer and NC stands for non-cancer.
[src:behavior-trees/decision-tree] The letter M stands for mutation, and if a sample has a particular mutation it will show up in the table as a one and otherwise zero.
[src:behavior-trees/decision-tree] Now, we can use the formulas to calculate the phi function values and information gain values for each M in the dataset.
[src:behavior-trees/decision-tree] Once all the values are calculated the tree can be produced.
[src:behavior-trees/decision-tree] The first thing to be done is to select the root node.
[src:behavior-trees/decision-tree] In information gain and the phi function we consider the optimal split to be the mutation that produces the highest value for information gain or the phi function.
[src:behavior-trees/decision-tree] Now assume that M1 has the highest phi function value and M4 has the highest information gain value.
[src:behavior-trees/decision-tree] The M1 mutation will be the root of our phi function tree and M4 will be the root of our information gain tree.
[src:behavior-trees/decision-tree] Now, once we have chosen the root node we can split the samples into two groups based on whether a sample is positive or negative for the root node mutation.
[src:behavior-trees/decision-tree] The groups will be called group A and group B.
[src:behavior-trees/decision-tree] For example, if we use M1 to split the samples in the root node we get NC2 and C2 samples in group A and the rest of the samples NC4, NC3, NC1, C1 in group B.
[src:behavior-trees/decision-tree] Disregarding the mutation chosen for the root node, proceed to place the next best features that have the highest values for information gain or the phi function in the left or right child nodes of the decision tree.
[src:behavior-trees/decision-tree] Once we choose the root node and the two child nodes for the tree of depth = 3 we can just add the leaves.
[src:behavior-trees/decision-tree] The leaves will represent the final classification decision the model has produced based on the mutations a sample either has or does not have.
[src:behavior-trees/decision-tree] The left tree is the decision tree we obtain from using information gain to split the nodes and the right tree is what we obtain from using the phi function to split the nodes.
[src:behavior-trees/decision-tree] Now assume the classification results from both trees are given using a confusion matrix.
[src:behavior-trees/decision-tree] The tree using information gain has the same results when using the phi function when calculating the accuracy.
[src:behavior-trees/decision-tree] When we classify the samples based on the model using information gain we get one true positive, one false positive, zero false negatives, and four true negatives.
[src:behavior-trees/decision-tree] For the model using the phi function we get two true positives, zero false positives, one false negative, and three true negatives.
[src:behavior-trees/decision-tree] The next step is to evaluate the effectiveness of the decision tree using some key metrics that will be discussed in the evaluating a decision tree section below.
[src:behavior-trees/decision-tree] The metrics that will be discussed below can help determine the next steps to be taken when optimizing the decision tree.
[src:behavior-trees/decision-tree] The above information is not where it ends for building and optimizing a decision tree.
[src:behavior-trees/decision-tree] There are many techniques for improving the decision tree classification models we build.
[src:behavior-trees/decision-tree] One of the techniques is making our decision tree model from a bootstrapped dataset.
[src:behavior-trees/decision-tree] The bootstrapped dataset helps remove the bias that occurs when building a decision tree model with the same data the model is tested with.
[src:behavior-trees/decision-tree] The ability to leverage the power of random forests can also help significantly improve the overall accuracy of the model being built.
[src:behavior-trees/decision-tree] This method generates many decisions from many decision trees and tallies up the votes from each decision tree to make the final classification.
[src:behavior-trees/decision-tree] There are many techniques, but the main objective is to test building your decision tree model in different ways to make sure it reaches the highest performance level possible.
[src:behavior-trees/decision-tree] It is important to know the measurements used to evaluate decision trees.
[src:behavior-trees/decision-tree] The main metrics used are accuracy, sensitivity, specificity, precision, miss rate, false discovery rate, and false omission rate.
[src:behavior-trees/decision-tree] All these measurements are derived from the number of true positives, false positives, True negatives, and false negatives obtained when running a set of samples through the decision tree classification model.
[src:behavior-trees/decision-tree] Also, a confusion matrix can be made to display these results.
[src:behavior-trees/decision-tree] All these main metrics tell something different about the strengths and weaknesses of the classification model built based on your decision tree.
[src:behavior-trees/decision-tree] For example, a low sensitivity with high specificity could indicate the classification model built from the decision tree does not do well identifying cancer samples over non-cancer samples.
[src:behavior-trees/decision-tree] We will now calculate the values accuracy, sensitivity, specificity, precision, miss rate, false discovery rate, and false omission rate.
[src:behavior-trees/decision-tree] Once we have calculated the key metrics we can make some initial conclusions on the performance of the decision tree model built.
[src:behavior-trees/decision-tree] The accuracy that we calculated was 71.60%.
[src:behavior-trees/decision-tree] The accuracy value is good to start but we would like to get our models as accurate as possible while maintaining the overall performance.
[src:behavior-trees/decision-tree] The sensitivity value of 19.64% means that out of everyone who was actually positive for cancer tested positive.
[src:behavior-trees/decision-tree] If we look at the specificity value of 99.06% we know that out of all the samples that were negative for cancer actually tested negative.
[src:behavior-trees/decision-tree] When it comes to sensitivity and specificity it is important to have a balance between the two values, so if we can decrease our specificity to increase the sensitivity that would prove to be beneficial.
[src:behavior-trees/decision-tree] These are just a few examples on how to use these values and the meanings behind them to evaluate the decision tree model and improve upon the next iteration.
[src:behavior-trees/finite-state-machine] In theoretical computer science, a **finite-state machine** (**FSM**) or **finite-state automaton** (**FSA**, plural: *automata*), **finite automaton**, or simply a **state machine**, is a mathematical model of computation.
[src:behavior-trees/finite-state-machine] It is an abstract machine that can be in exactly one of a finite number of *states* at any given time.
[src:behavior-trees/finite-state-machine] The FSM can change from one state to another in response to some inputs; the change from one state to another is called a *transition*.
[src:behavior-trees/finite-state-machine] An FSM is defined by a list of its states, its initial state, and the inputs that trigger each transition.
[src:behavior-trees/finite-state-machine] Finite-state machines are of two types—deterministic finite-state machines and non-deterministic finite-state machines.
[src:behavior-trees/finite-state-machine] For any non-deterministic finite-state machine, an equivalent deterministic one can be constructed.
[src:behavior-trees/finite-state-machine] The behavior of state machines can be observed in many devices in modern society that perform a predetermined sequence of actions depending on a sequence of events with which they are presented.
[src:behavior-trees/finite-state-machine] The finite-state machine has less computational power than some other models of computation such as the Turing machine.
[src:behavior-trees/finite-state-machine] The computational power distinction means there are computational tasks that a Turing machine can do but an FSM cannot.
[src:behavior-trees/finite-state-machine] This is because an FSM's memory is limited by the number of states it has.
[src:behavior-trees/finite-state-machine] A finite-state machine has the same computational power as a Turing machine that is restricted such that its head may only perform "read" operations, and always has to move from left to right.
[src:behavior-trees/finite-state-machine] FSMs are studied in the more general field of automata theory.
[src:behavior-trees/finite-state-machine] An example of a simple mechanism that can be modeled by a state machine is a turnstile.
[src:behavior-trees/finite-state-machine] A turnstile, used to control access to subways and amusement park rides, is a gate with three rotating arms at waist height, one across the entryway.
[src:behavior-trees/finite-state-machine] Initially the arms are locked, blocking the entry, preventing patrons from passing through.
[src:behavior-trees/finite-state-machine] Depositing a coin or token in a slot on the turnstile unlocks the arms, allowing a single customer to push through.
[src:behavior-trees/finite-state-machine] After the customer passes through, the arms are locked again until another coin is inserted.
[src:behavior-trees/finite-state-machine] Considered as a state machine, the turnstile has two possible states: *Locked* and *Unlocked*.
[src:behavior-trees/finite-state-machine] There are two possible inputs that affect its state: putting a coin in the slot (*coin*) and pushing the arm (*push*).
[src:behavior-trees/finite-state-machine] In the locked state, pushing on the arm has no effect; no matter how many times the input *push* is given, it stays in the locked state.
[src:behavior-trees/finite-state-machine] Putting a coin in – that is, giving the machine a *coin* input – shifts the state from *Locked* to *Unlocked*.
[src:behavior-trees/finite-state-machine] In the unlocked state, putting additional coins in has no effect; that is, giving additional *coin* inputs does not change the state.
[src:behavior-trees/finite-state-machine] A customer pushing through the arms gives a *push* input and resets the state to *Locked*.
[src:behavior-trees/finite-state-machine] The turnstile state machine can also be represented by a directed graph called a state diagram *(above)*.
[src:behavior-trees/finite-state-machine] Each state is represented by a node (*circle*).
[src:behavior-trees/finite-state-machine] Edges (*arrows*) show the transitions from one state to another.
[src:behavior-trees/finite-state-machine] Each arrow is labeled with the input that triggers that transition.
[src:behavior-trees/finite-state-machine] An input that doesn't cause a change of state (such as a *coin* input in the *Unlocked* state) is represented by a circular arrow returning to the original state.
[src:behavior-trees/finite-state-machine] The arrow into the *Locked* node from the black dot indicates it is the initial state.
[src:behavior-trees/finite-state-machine] A *state* is a description of the status of a system that is waiting to execute a *transition*.
[src:behavior-trees/finite-state-machine] A transition is a set of actions to be executed when a condition is fulfilled or when an event is received.
[src:behavior-trees/finite-state-machine] For example, when using an audio system to listen to the radio (the system is in the "radio" state), receiving a "next" stimulus results in moving to the next station.
[src:behavior-trees/finite-state-machine] When the system is in the "CD" state, the "next" stimulus results in moving to the next track.
[src:behavior-trees/finite-state-machine] Identical stimuli trigger different actions depending on the current state.
[src:behavior-trees/finite-state-machine] Several state-transition table types are used.
[src:behavior-trees/finite-state-machine] The most common representation is shown below: the combination of current state (e.g.
[src:behavior-trees/finite-state-machine] By itself, the table cannot completely describe the action, so it is common to use footnotes.
[src:behavior-trees/finite-state-machine] Other related representations may not have this limitation.
[src:behavior-trees/finite-state-machine] For example, an FSM definition including the full action's information is possible using state tables (see also virtual finite-state machine).
[src:behavior-trees/finite-state-machine] The Unified Modeling Language has a notation for describing state machines.
[src:behavior-trees/finite-state-machine] UML state machines overcome the limitations of traditional finite-state machines while retaining their main benefits.
[src:behavior-trees/finite-state-machine] UML state machines introduce the new concepts of hierarchically nested states and orthogonal regions, while extending the notion of actions.
[src:behavior-trees/finite-state-machine] UML state machines have the characteristics of both Mealy machines and Moore machines.
[src:behavior-trees/finite-state-machine] They support actions that depend on both the state of the system and the triggering event, as in Mealy machines, as well as entry and exit actions, which are associated with states rather than transitions, as in Moore machines.
[src:behavior-trees/finite-state-machine] SDL embeds basic data types called "Abstract Data Types", an action language, and an execution semantic in order to make the finite-state machine executable.
[src:behavior-trees/finite-state-machine] There are a large number of variants to represent an FSM such as the one in figure 3.
[src:behavior-trees/finite-state-machine] In addition to their use in modeling reactive systems presented here, finite-state machines are significant in many different areas, including electrical engineering, linguistics, computer science, philosophy, biology, mathematics, video game programming, and logic.
[src:behavior-trees/finite-state-machine] Finite-state machines are a class of automata studied in automata theory and the theory of computation.
[src:behavior-trees/finite-state-machine] In computer science, finite-state machines are widely used in modeling of application behavior (control theory), design of hardware digital systems, software engineering, compilers, network protocols, and computational linguistics.
[src:behavior-trees/finite-state-machine] Finite-state machines can be subdivided into acceptors, classifiers, transducers and sequencers.
[src:behavior-trees/finite-state-machine] A (possibly infinite) set of symbol sequences, called a formal language, is a regular language if there is some acceptor that accepts *exactly* that set.
[src:behavior-trees/finite-state-machine] For example, the set of binary strings with an even number of zeroes is a regular language (cf.
[src:behavior-trees/finite-state-machine] 5), while the set of all strings whose length is a prime number is not.
[src:behavior-trees/finite-state-machine] An acceptor could also be described as defining a language that would contain every string accepted by the acceptor but none of the rejected ones; that language is *accepted* by the acceptor.
[src:behavior-trees/finite-state-machine] By definition, the languages accepted by acceptors are the regular languages.
[src:behavior-trees/finite-state-machine] The problem of determining the language accepted by a given acceptor is an instance of the algebraic path problem—itself a generalization of the shortest path problem to graphs with edges weighted by the elements of an (arbitrary) semiring.
[src:behavior-trees/finite-state-machine] An example of an accepting state appears in Fig.
[src:behavior-trees/finite-state-machine] 5: a deterministic finite automaton (DFA) that detects whether the binary input string contains an even number of 0s.
[src:behavior-trees/finite-state-machine] The FSM uses only entry actions, i.e., output depends only on state.
[src:behavior-trees/finite-state-machine] The advantage of the Moore model is a simplification of the behaviour.
[src:behavior-trees/finite-state-machine] The state machine recognizes two commands: "command_open" and "command_close", which trigger state changes.
[src:behavior-trees/finite-state-machine] The entry action (E:) in state "Opening" starts a motor opening the door, the entry action in state "Closing" starts a motor in the other direction closing the door.
[src:behavior-trees/finite-state-machine] States "Opened" and "Closed" stop the motor when fully opened or closed.
[src:behavior-trees/finite-state-machine] They signal to the outside world (e.g., to other state machines) the situation: "door is open" or "door is closed".
[src:behavior-trees/finite-state-machine] The FSM also uses input actions, i.e., output depends on input and state.
[src:behavior-trees/finite-state-machine] The use of a Mealy FSM leads often to a reduction of the number of states.
[src:behavior-trees/finite-state-machine] There are two input actions (I:): "start motor to close the door if command_close arrives" and "start motor in the other direction to open the door if command_open arrives".
[src:behavior-trees/finite-state-machine] The "opening" and "closing" intermediate states are not shown.
[src:behavior-trees/finite-state-machine] A further distinction is between *deterministic* (DFA) and *non-deterministic* (NFA, GNFA) automata.
[src:behavior-trees/finite-state-machine] In a deterministic automaton, every state has exactly one transition for each possible input.
[src:behavior-trees/finite-state-machine] In a non-deterministic automaton, an input can lead to one, more than one, or no transition for a given state.
[src:behavior-trees/finite-state-machine] The powerset construction algorithm can transform any nondeterministic automaton into a (usually more complex) deterministic automaton with identical functionality.
[src:behavior-trees/finite-state-machine] A finite-state machine with only one state is called a "combinatorial FSM".
[src:behavior-trees/finite-state-machine] It only allows actions upon transition *into* a state.
[src:behavior-trees/finite-state-machine] This concept is useful in cases where a number of finite-state machines are required to work together, and when it is convenient to consider a purely combinatorial part as a form of FSM to suit the design tools.
[src:behavior-trees/finite-state-machine] There are other sets of semantics available to represent state machines.
[src:behavior-trees/finite-state-machine] For example, there are tools for modeling and designing logic for embedded controllers.
[src:behavior-trees/finite-state-machine] They combine hierarchical state machines (which usually have more than one current state), flow graphs, and truth tables into one language, resulting in a different formalism and set of semantics.
[src:behavior-trees/finite-state-machine] These charts, like Harel's original state machines, support hierarchically nested states, orthogonal regions, state actions, and transition actions.
[src:behavior-trees/finite-state-machine] In accordance with the general classification, the following formal definitions are found.
[src:behavior-trees/finite-state-machine] For both deterministic and non-deterministic FSMs, it is conventional to allow $\delta$ to be a partial function, i.e. $\delta (s,x)$ does not have to be defined for every combination of $s\in S$ and $x\in \Sigma$ .
[src:behavior-trees/finite-state-machine] If an FSM M is in a state s , the next symbol is x and $\delta (s,x)$ is not defined, then M can announce an error (i.e. reject the input).
[src:behavior-trees/finite-state-machine] This is useful in definitions of general state machines, but less useful when transforming the machine.
[src:behavior-trees/finite-state-machine] Some algorithms in their default form may require total functions.
[src:behavior-trees/finite-state-machine] That is, each formal language accepted by a finite-state machine is accepted by such a kind of restricted Turing machine, and vice versa.
[src:behavior-trees/finite-state-machine] If the output function depends on the state and input symbol ( $\omega :S\times \Sigma \rightarrow \Gamma$ ) that definition corresponds to the *Mealy model*, and can be modelled as a Mealy machine.
[src:behavior-trees/finite-state-machine] If the output function depends only on the state ( $\omega :S\rightarrow \Gamma$ ) that definition corresponds to the *Moore model*, and can be modelled as a Moore machine.
[src:behavior-trees/finite-state-machine] A finite-state machine with no output function at all is known as a semiautomaton or transition system.
[src:behavior-trees/finite-state-machine] If we disregard the first output symbol of a Moore machine, $\omega (s_{0})$ , then it can be readily converted to an output-equivalent Mealy machine by setting the output function of every Mealy transition (i.e. labeling every edge) with the output symbol given of the destination Moore state.
[src:behavior-trees/finite-state-machine] The converse transformation is less straightforward because a Mealy machine state may have different output labels on its incoming transitions (edges).
[src:behavior-trees/finite-state-machine] Every such state needs to be split in multiple Moore machine states, one for every incident output symbol.
[src:behavior-trees/finite-state-machine] Optimizing an FSM means finding a machine with the minimum number of states that performs the same function.
[src:behavior-trees/finite-state-machine] The fastest known algorithm doing this is the Hopcroft minimization algorithm.
[src:behavior-trees/finite-state-machine] Other techniques include using an implication table, or the Moore reduction procedure.
[src:behavior-trees/finite-state-machine] Additionally, acyclic FSAs can be minimized in linear time.
[src:behavior-trees/finite-state-machine] In a digital circuit, an FSM may be built using a programmable logic device, a programmable logic controller, logic gates and flip flops or relays.
[src:behavior-trees/finite-state-machine] More specifically, a hardware implementation requires a register to store state variables, a block of combinational logic that determines the state transition, and a second block of combinational logic that determines the output of an FSM.
[src:behavior-trees/finite-state-machine] In a *Medvedev machine*, the output is directly connected to the state flip-flops minimizing the time delay between flip-flops and output.
[src:behavior-trees/finite-state-machine] Through state encoding for low power state machines may be optimized to minimize power consumption.
[src:behavior-trees/finite-state-machine] Finite automata are often used in the frontend of programming language compilers.
[src:behavior-trees/finite-state-machine] Such a frontend may comprise several finite-state machines that implement a lexical analyzer and a parser.
[src:behavior-trees/finite-state-machine] Starting from a sequence of characters, the lexical analyzer builds a sequence of language tokens (such as reserved words, literals, and identifiers) from which the parser builds a syntax tree.
[src:behavior-trees/finite-state-machine] The lexical analyzer and the parser handle the regular and context-free parts of the programming language's grammar.
